if ! [[ $HOSTTYPE == x86_64 ]]; then return; fi
if ! [[ -f /lib/libc.so.6   ]]; then return; fi
if   [[ -z "$MONOLIB_LOGS"  ]]; then return; fi

HELP=$"
monolib	on	*	Give monolib trait to spells on stdin
monolib	off	*	Omit monolib trait to spells on stdin
monolib	[none]	 	Spells assigned monolib trait"


LONG=$"
monolib is a command for x86_64 multilib boxes.
Spells that have both the library and monolib traits
will not do an ELF 32-bit compilation
and will not install ELF 32-bit libraries.
The effect of assigning a spell the monolib trait is recursive.
Therefore, all trait library spells
that require a spell that is monolib also become monolib.

The inspiration for the monolib command
is to allow SAs to trim the time for updating
and space required for an installation of KDE4
on multilib boxes by not installing multilib KDE4.
To create this effect a SA must run:

# echo qt-everywhere-opensource | augur monolib on

Then not only will qt-everywhere-opensource
gain the monolib trait, but also any spell
that requires qt-everywhere-opensource
will also gain monolib and not install ELF 32-bit libraries.

Please carefully consider which spells are given the monolib trait.
Compile errors might result on boxes where
the selection was not anticipated

# echo \$SPELL | augur req iron

Assuming \$SPELL is being assigned monolib
then the list output from the above command
are also all the other spells that are effected.
Assigning monolib to db gdbm or perl
will also cause the next cast of glibc
to install only 64-bit libraries.
When glibc is is no longer multilib
then all installed software recasts pure 64-bit.
Pure x86_64 is fine for many boxes,
but is not doable not for a box that uses wine
or uses other 32-bit software.

Again please be careful.
Make backups.
Already one Sorcerer SA reduced his multilib box
to pure x86_64 by assigning monolib to perl.
He used backups to restore the box to a multilib state.
No assistance is provided to SAs that make
their boxes pure 64-bit and want to return it to multilib.
So if recovery is not a pre-planned simple 5 minute task
then perhaps using monolib should be avoided.
"

param(){ echo "on${LF}off" | grep -i "^$1"; }

run(){
 run_on(){
  mkdir -pm 755 $MONOLIB_LOGS
  while read; do touch $MONOLIB_LOGS/$REPLY; done
 }

 run_off(){
  while read; do rm -f $MONOLIB_LOGS/$REPLY; done
  rmdir --ignore-fail-on-non-empty $MONOLIB_LOGS
 }

 run_list(){
  if   [ -d "$MONOLIB_LOGS" ]
  then find $MONOLIB_LOGS/ -type f -printf '%f\n'
  fi
 }

 case "$1" in
  on)  run_on   ;;
  off) run_off  ;;
  *)   run_list ;;
 esac
}
